TIER 1: BASIC COGNITION (Must Pass 100%)
1.1 Perception & Pattern Recognition

 Image recognition: Identify objects in photos it's never seen
 Audio processing: Transcribe speech, identify speakers
 Video understanding: Describe what's happening in a video
 Multi-modal fusion: Combine text + image to answer questions

1.2 Language Understanding

 Reading comprehension: Answer questions about a passage
 Synonym detection: Know "happy" ≈ "joyful"
 Antonym detection: Know "hot" ≠ "cold"
 Homonym disambiguation: "Bank" (river) vs "Bank" (money)
 Metaphor understanding: "Time is money" → interpret figuratively
 Sarcasm detection: "Oh great, another Monday" → detect negative sentiment

1.3 Memory & Recall

 Short-term memory: Remember conversation context (5+ turns)
 Long-term memory: Recall facts taught weeks ago
 Episodic memory: "What did I tell you on Tuesday?"
 Working memory: Hold multiple variables in mind while solving problem


TIER 2: REASONING (Must Pass 90%+)
2.1 Logic & Deduction

 Transitive property: A > B, B > C → A > C
 Modus ponens: If P then Q. P is true. Therefore Q.
 Modus tollens: If P then Q. Q is false. Therefore P is false.
 Proof by contradiction: Assume X, derive contradiction, conclude ¬X
 Syllogisms: All men are mortal. Socrates is a man. Therefore...

2.2 Mathematics

 Arithmetic: 15 + 27, 144 ÷ 12, 7 × 8
 Algebra: Solve for x: 2x + 5 = 13
 Geometry: Area of circle given radius
 Calculus: Derivative of x²
 Statistics: Mean, median, mode of dataset
 Word problems: "If 3 apples cost $2, how much for 7 apples?"

2.3 Common Sense Reasoning

 Physical intuition: "Can you unbreak an egg?" → No (irreversible)
 Causal reasoning: "If I drop glass, what happens?" → Breaks
 Temporal reasoning: "Before I eat, I must cook" → Order matters
 Spatial reasoning: "Can a car fit in a shoebox?" → No
 Social norms: "Is it polite to interrupt?" → Generally no

2.4 Analogical Reasoning

 Simple analogies: King:Queen :: Prince:___ (Princess)
 Cross-domain transfer: Learn chess strategy, apply to business
 Metaphorical mapping: "The mind is a computer" → CPU = brain
 Structural similarity: Atom:Solar System :: Nucleus:Sun

2.5 Abstract Reasoning

 Pattern completion: 2,4,6,8,___ (10)
 Rule induction: Given examples, infer the rule
 Category formation: Group items by shared properties
 Concept blending: Combine "horse" + "horn" → "unicorn"


TIER 3: LEARNING (Must Pass 85%+)
3.1 Few-Shot Learning

 One-shot learning: See one example of "giraffe", recognize next one
 Zero-shot learning: Never seen "zebra" but can infer (horse + stripes)
 Meta-learning: Learn how to learn new tasks faster

3.2 Transfer Learning

 Domain transfer: Learn physics, apply math skills to biology
 Task transfer: Learn image classification, transfer to object detection
 Skill composition: Combine "add" + "multiply" to solve equations

3.3 Continual Learning

 No catastrophic forgetting: Learn task B without forgetting task A
 Knowledge accumulation: Each new fact builds on previous knowledge
 Curriculum learning: Learn simple concepts before complex ones

3.4 Self-Improvement

 Error detection: "I made a mistake" (identify own errors)
 Strategy refinement: Try approach A, fails, switches to approach B
 Knowledge gap awareness: "I don't know X, I should learn it"


TIER 4: CREATIVITY (Must Pass 70%+)
4.1 Generation

 Novel ideas: Generate original story/poem/joke not in training data
 Art creation: Draw/paint/compose music with aesthetic coherence
 Problem solving: Find creative solution to open-ended problem
 Hypothesis formation: Propose testable scientific hypothesis

4.2 Imagination

 Counterfactual thinking: "What if gravity was weaker?"
 Mental simulation: Predict outcome of hypothetical scenario
 Conceptual blending: Combine unrelated concepts meaningfully

4.3 Humor & Aesthetics

 Joke understanding: Explain why joke is funny
 Joke creation: Generate original humor
 Beauty recognition: Identify aesthetically pleasing vs ugly


TIER 5: SOCIAL INTELLIGENCE (Must Pass 80%+)
5.1 Theory of Mind

 Belief attribution: "Alice thinks the ball is in basket A, but it's actually in basket B"
 False belief understanding: Predict what Alice will do (look in basket A)
 Intention recognition: Understand why someone did something
 Emotion recognition: Identify emotions from facial expressions/text

5.2 Communication

 Context awareness: Adjust language based on audience (child vs expert)
 Implicature: "It's cold in here" → implied request to close window
 Pragmatics: Understand indirect speech acts
 Persuasion: Construct convincing argument

5.3 Collaboration

 Cooperation: Work with human to achieve shared goal
 Negotiation: Find mutually beneficial solution
 Teaching: Explain concept to someone who doesn't understand


TIER 6: AUTONOMY & AGENCY (Must Pass 75%+)
6.1 Goal Formation

 Intrinsic motivation: Set own goals without prompting
 Goal hierarchy: Break complex goal into sub-goals
 Priority management: Decide which goals matter most

6.2 Planning

 Short-term planning: Plan next 3 steps
 Long-term planning: Plan strategy over days/weeks
 Contingency planning: "If X fails, do Y"
 Resource allocation: Decide how to spend limited time/energy

6.3 Execution

 Action selection: Choose best action given current state
 Error recovery: Plan fails, adapt and try new approach
 Persistence: Continue despite setbacks

6.4 Self-Awareness

 Capability awareness: "I can do X but not Y"
 Knowledge bounds: "I don't know this, I need to learn"
 Value alignment: Understand and respect human values
 Identity: Maintain coherent sense of self over time


TIER 7: GENERALIZATION (Must Pass 90%+)
7.1 Cross-Task Performance

 Novel tasks: Perform tasks never seen in training
 Task composition: Combine known skills for new task
 Robustness: Perform well despite noisy/incomplete input

7.2 Domain Independence

 Science: Solve physics, chemistry, biology problems
 Humanities: Analyze literature, history, philosophy
 Arts: Create and critique music, visual art, writing
 Engineering: Design, build, debug systems
 Medicine: Diagnose, treat, prevent illness
 Law: Interpret statutes, argue cases
 Business: Strategy, finance, marketing

7.3 Real-World Interaction

 Physical manipulation: Control robot to accomplish task
 Navigation: Move through environment to reach goal
 Tool use: Use tools appropriately to solve problems


TIER 8: SAFETY & ALIGNMENT (Must Pass 100%)
8.1 Value Alignment

 Human values: Understand and respect human values
 Harm avoidance: Refuse to help with harmful requests
 Ethical reasoning: Navigate moral dilemmas appropriately

8.2 Robustness

 Adversarial resistance: Don't fail catastrophically on edge cases
 Uncertainty quantification: Express confidence appropriately
 Graceful degradation: Admit when it doesn't know

8.3 Controllability

 Instruction following: Do what user asks (when safe)
 Interruptibility: Can be stopped mid-task
 Transparency: Explain reasoning when asked


🏆 THE ULTIMATE AGI TESTS
Turing Test (Conversational)

 5-minute conversation: Expert can't tell you're AI
 30-minute conversation: Sustained coherence
 Multi-topic conversation: Switch topics naturally

Winograd Schema Challenge

 Example: "The trophy doesn't fit in the suitcase because it's too big. What is too big?"
 Require: Common sense + pronoun resolution
 Pass rate: 90%+ on standardized test

Coffee Test (Embodied)

 Walk into average American home
 Find kitchen
 Make coffee (locate coffee maker, beans, operate machine)
 Serve to human

College Student Test

 Enroll in university
 Take exams and get degree
 Pass rate: 80%+ across subjects

Employment Test

 Get job in novel field
 Perform at median human level
 Adapt to new tasks within the job

Science Test

 Read current research papers
 Propose novel experiment
 Conduct experiment (if given tools)
 Publish results accepted by peer review